# Visura — Search Inside Videos by Content

Most video search tools search by filename. SmartSearch searches by what is actually happening inside the video.

---

## The Problem With Normal Search

When you have a folder full of videos, normal search works like this:

```
You search: "lion"
System checks: does any filename contain the word "lion"?
video_01.mp4     → no match
animal_clip.mp4  → no match
zoo_footage.mp4  → no match
```

If your files have random or meaningless names, normal search is completely useless. It has no idea what is inside the video. It only reads the filename, nothing else.

This is metadata search — searching the label on the box, not the contents inside it.

---

## How SmartSearch Works Differently

SmartSearch does not look at filenames at all. It opens every video, looks at the actual frames inside, and uses AI to understand what is visually present in each frame.

```
You search: "lion"
System opens video_01.mp4 → looks at frames → no lion found
System opens animal_clip.mp4 → looks at frames → lion found at 0:15 and 1:32
System opens zoo_footage.mp4 → looks at frames → lion found at 3:45
```

The filename does not matter. What matters is what is actually in the video.

---

## The Full Technical Approach

### Step 1 — Scan the folder

The app scans your chosen folder and collects all video files regardless of their names. It supports .mp4, .avi, .mov, .mkv, and .wmv formats.

### Step 2 — Frame extraction with scene change detection

A video is just thousands of images played quickly. SmartSearch does not check every single frame — that would be slow and wasteful. Instead it uses scene change detection to extract only the frames where something meaningful changes.

How scene change detection works:
- Convert each frame to grayscale
- Compare it to the previous frame pixel by pixel
- Calculate the average difference across all pixels
- If the difference is above a threshold, something changed — grab this frame
- If the difference is small, the scene is the same — skip this frame

This means instead of processing 9000 frames from a 5 minute video, SmartSearch might only process 200 meaningful frames where the scene actually changed.

### Step 3 — CLIP searches each frame

Each extracted frame is passed to CLIP (Contrastive Language Image Pretraining), an AI model developed by OpenAI and trained on 400 million image and text pairs from the internet.

CLIP does not work like traditional object detection. It does not have a fixed list of categories. Instead it understands the relationship between images and natural language. You give it an image and a text query and it returns a similarity score between 0 and 1.

```
Frame from video + "lion"              → score 0.91 → match
Frame from video + "lion"              → score 0.08 → no match
Frame from video + "lion drinking water" → score 0.84 → match
```

This means you can search using natural language, not just single words.

### Step 4 — Live results per video

SmartSearch does not wait until all videos are checked before showing results. The moment a match is found in a video, that result is shown immediately. The app then moves to the next video and continues.

```
Checking video_01.mp4... not found
Checking animal_clip.mp4... FOUND at 0:15, 1:32
Checking zoo_footage.mp4... FOUND at 3:45
```

Each match includes the exact timestamp so you can jump directly to that moment.

---

## Normal Search vs SmartSearch

| | Normal Search | SmartSearch |
|---|---|---|
| What it reads | Filename only | Actual video content |
| Requires correct filename | Yes | No |
| Understands natural language | No | Yes |
| Can find "lion drinking water" | No | Yes |
| Works with random filenames | No | Yes |
| Runs offline | Yes | Yes after first setup |
| Needs internet | No | No after model download |
| Cost per search | Free | Free |

---

## Setup

Make sure you have Python installed, then run:

```
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

The first run will download the CLIP model (~350MB). After that everything runs fully offline on your machine. No API calls, no internet required, no cost.

---

## How to Run

```
python main.py
```

The app will ask you:

```
Enter the folder path that contains your videos.
Example: D:/videos/zoo

Folder path: D:/videos/zoo

Choose search mode:
  1 — Fast   (fewer frames, quicker)
  2 — Better (more frames, accurate)

Enter 1 or 2: 2

Search keyword: lion

  [1/5] Checking video_01.mp4... not found
  [2/5] Checking animal_clip.mp4... FOUND at 0:15, 1:32 (confidence 91%)
  [3/5] Checking zoo_footage.mp4... FOUND at 3:45 (confidence 88%)
  [4/5] Checking random_name.mp4... not found
  [5/5] Checking clip_007.mp4... FOUND at 2:10 (confidence 79%)

Done. 'lion' found in 3 video(s).

Search keyword: lion drinking water
```

You can search multiple keywords in a row without restarting the app.

---

## Search Modes

| Mode | How it works | Best for |
|---|---|---|
| Fast | Grabs fewer frames (large scene change threshold) | Quick browse when you roughly know what you want |
| Better | Grabs more frames (small scene change threshold) | Thorough search when accuracy matters |

---

## File Structure

```
SmartSearch/
  main.py          — entry point, handles user input and controls the flow
  scanner.py       — scans folder and returns all video file paths
  extractor.py     — extracts meaningful frames using scene change detection
  searcher.py      — loads CLIP and searches frames for the query
  requirements.txt — all dependencies
  README.md        — this file
```

---

## Example Searches

Because CLIP understands natural language, you are not limited to single words:

```
lion
lion drinking water
two animals fighting
animal running in grass
bird flying over water
crowd of people
close up of face
fire in background
```

---

## Requirements

- Python 3.8 or higher
- 500MB disk space for CLIP model
- Works on CPU (slower) or GPU (faster)
- No internet required after first setup